📁 File Handling in C :

Welcome to the File Handling module of my C Programming journey. This folder contains robust implementations of persistent data storage, demonstrating how to bridge the gap between volatile RAM and permanent disk storage.

📝 Description:

File handling is a crucial concept in C that allows a program to save data permanently. This repository focuses on mastering the stdio.h file operations, ensuring data integrity, and implementing efficient I/O (Input/Output) patterns.

🚀 Key Features Implemented
Persistent Storage: Moving beyond runtime memory to save data in .txt and .dat formats.

File Modes: Practical implementation of various access modes:

"r" (Read): Accessing existing data safely.

"w" (Write): Creating new files and overwriting data.

"a" (Append): Adding new information to the end of existing files without data loss.

Formatted I/O: Using fprintf() and fscanf() for structured data management.

Error Handling: Implementing NULL pointer checks and feof() to handle "File Not Found" or "End of File" scenarios gracefully.

Stream Management: Ensuring zero memory leaks by always using fclose() to free system resources.

🛠️ Technical Concepts Covered :
File Pointers: Understanding FILE *fp and its lifecycle.

Buffer Management: How C handles data streams between the program and the hard drive.

Sequential Access: Reading and writing data line-by-line using fgets() and fputs().

📊 Learning Outcomes:

Through this module, I have mastered the ability to create programs that can "remember" data even after the computer is turned off.
This is a stepping stone toward building real-world applications like Database Management Systems and Log Analyzers.

